results.male_result:
Values exhibit extreme variation based on Tanner stage (pubertal development) and are significantly higher than adults. Typical ranges for adolescents (10-19 years) encompass the peak growth spurt (approx. age 13-15) and the subsequent decline. 
Bone Formation Markers: 
Osteocalcin (OC): 20 - 160 ng/mL; 
Bone-specific Alkaline Phosphatase (BSAP): 20 - 120 μg/L; 
Procollagen Type I N-terminal Propeptide (P1NP): 100 - 900 ng/mL. 
Bone Resorption Markers: 
C-terminal Telopeptide of Type I Collagen (CTX): 0.5 - 2.8 ng/mL; 
N-terminal Telopeptide of Type I Collagen (NTX): 10 - 120 nM BCE/L.

results.female_result:
Values exhibit extreme variation based on Tanner stage and are significantly higher than adults, but peak earlier than males (approx. age 11-13) and decline rapidly after menarche. 
Bone Formation Markers: 
Osteocalcin (OC): 15 - 130 ng/mL; 
Bone-specific Alkaline Phosphatase (BSAP): 15 - 90 μg/L; 
Procollagen Type I N-terminal Propeptide (P1NP): 80 - 700 ng/mL. 
Bone Resorption Markers: 
C-terminal Telopeptide of Type I Collagen (CTX): 0.4 - 2.0 ng/mL; 
N-terminal Telopeptide of Type I Collagen (NTX): 10 - 100 nM BCE/L.
